[!INFO] Liddle syndrome (aka Pseudohyperaldosteronism)

  • Mnemonic: Liddles -> Luminal membran ENaC Channels
  • Gain of function mutation of ENaC Channels -> Sodium retention + Hypertension + Hypokalemia + metabolic alkalosis.
  • Treated with amiloride or triamterine, low sodium diet.
  • Spironolactone won't work because as an aldosterone antagonist, it won't affect the activity of the mutated ENaC channels.
  • No SHAME in going to Lidl
  • Sodium channel, Hypokalemia, Amiloride, Mutation, Early onset hypertension
  • Also has low renin level

Usual presentation: Patient can't wake up after sleeping after a heavy dinner.

  • Normal skeletal muscle becomes hyperexcitable during hypokalemia.
  • However, in HPP, skeletal muscle becomes unexcitable during hypokalemia.
  • Typical history: patient develops acute paralysis (lower limb > upper limb, areflexia) following carbohydrate heavy meal or heavy exercise.
  • Women more affected than men.
    [!INFO] Hyperkalemic periodic paralysis
  • problem in the sodium channels of muscles.
  • K+ shifts extracellularly
  • Causes muscle weakness or muscle rigidity
  • Rarer than Hypokalemic paralysis
  • Affects men and women equally.
  • Short episodes of muscle paralysis.
  • Frequency increases until 40 years old and then decreases.
  • Triggers: K+ rich foods, exercise.

Gitelman syndrome

[!INFO] AKA familial hypokalemia-hypomagnesaemia
Source

  • Local 5 amino salicilates are the mainstay of treatment for mild and moderate disease. (Mesalazine (aka mesalamine), Olsalazine, Balsazide, Sulfasalazine)
  • ⭐

[!INFO] Onion skin fibrosis:

  • Liver transplantation is the only treatment than can alter progression. Drugs won't work.
    - But ursodeoxycholic is the most promising agent. Source
    - Pruritus can be reduced with cholestyramine.
    • PSC without IBD is more likely to occur in women.
  • hypergammaglobulinaemia is present.
  • ultimately leads to cirrhosis.
  • Complications: Osteoporosis (fat soluble vitamins), cholangiocarcinoma, cholangitis.

  • Langerhans cells are antigen presenting cells but the abnormal cells in the disease have lower antigen presenting ability.
  • Birbeck granules present on EM: They have a "tennis racket" shape.
  • Is one cause of interstitial lung disease.
  • The disease involves the formation of multiple granulomas throughout the body.
    Adults commonly have single system involvement.
    • Only skin involvement -> Good prognosis; resection of local lesion can be curative.
    • Lung involvement -> bad prognosis
  • pituitary involvement -> commonest manifestation is diabetes insipidus.
  • Adults commonly have lytic lesions in the jaw and skull.
  • Upper and middle zone involvement is characteristic.
  • bone pain, typically in the skull or proximal femur

    Prognosis:

Diagnosis:

  • Skin biopsy
    Management:
  • Responds to chemotherapy.
- *Evidence is retricted* to those with **recent worsening of heart failure**
- oral soluble **guanylate cyclase stimulator** which enhances the cyclic guanosine monophosphate (**GMP**) pathway and *sensitizes soluble guanylate cyclase to endogenous nitric oxide*, resulting in pulmonary vasodilation [Source](https://www.msdmanuals.com/professional/cardiovascular-disorders/heart-failure/drugs-for-heart-failure)

Source

Metabolic syndrome

Core components of metabolic syndrome:

  1. Central obesity
  2. Hypertension
  3. Hyperglycaemia
  4. Central Obsesity
    NAFLD is considered the hepatic component of metabolic syndrome.

"arterial hypervascularity and venous / late phase washout"

[!TIP] Summary:

  • Resection is only for single lesions < 3cm with no hepatic effects
  • Ablation can be for single tiny lesions (<2cm) or if there are <= 3 lesions.

Mnemonic: CAB-EA
The CP score is used to predict prognosis in cirrhosis
